<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1747,2026]" box="[199,973,1855,1882]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1855,1881]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Description.</emphasis>
Body length 6.0– 
<quantity box="[546,634,1855,1882]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="6.7">6.7 mm</quantity>
; forebody length 
<quantity box="[831,969,1855,1882]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="3.6" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="3.25" valueMax="3.6" valueMin="2.9">2.9–3.6 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1747,2026]" box="[199,1163,1891,1918]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Body (Fig. 4) dark brown; legs yellowish brown; antennae dark brown to light brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1747,2026]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[272,352,1927,1953]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1497,1521]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,319,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-99@6.[151,1436,308,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Nazeris yujiei 23 forebody; 24 male sternite VII; 25 male sternite VIII; 26 aedeagus in ventral view; 27 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 23 1.0 mm; 24–27 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552225/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) 1.07–1.11 times as long as wide; punctation very dense, moderately coarse, distinctly umbilicate, interstices lacking microsculpture; postocular portion approximately 1.7–1.8 times as long as eye length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1747,2026]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[325,407,1999,2025]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1497,1521]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,319,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-99@6.[151,1436,308,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Nazeris yujiei 23 forebody; 24 male sternite VII; 25 male sternite VIII; 26 aedeagus in ventral view; 27 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 23 1.0 mm; 24–27 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552225/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) 1.16–1.20 times as long as wide, 0.97–1.00 times as long and 0.89–0.92 times as broad as head; punctation non-umbilicate, moderately dense and as coarse as that of head; midline posteriorly with short and narrow impunctate elevation; interstices lacking microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[286,370,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1497,1521]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,319,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-99@6.[151,1436,308,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Nazeris yujiei 23 forebody; 24 male sternite VII; 25 male sternite VIII; 26 aedeagus in ventral view; 27 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 23 1.0 mm; 24–27 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552225/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) 0.62–0.67 times as long as wide, 0.50–0.57 times as long and 0.97–1.00 times as broad as pronotum; punctation as dense as, and slightly coarser than that of pronotum; interstices lacking microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Abdomen with punctation dense and rather coarse on tergites III–V, dense and less coarse on tergite VI, moderately dense and fine on tergites VII–VIII; interstices lacking microsculpture.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
Male. Sternite VII (
<figureCitation box="[426,510,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1497,1521]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,319,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-99@6.[151,1436,308,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Nazeris yujiei 23 forebody; 24 male sternite VII; 25 male sternite VIII; 26 aedeagus in ventral view; 27 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 23 1.0 mm; 24–27 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552225/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) with posterior margin weakly prominent at middle. Sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1285,1369,366,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1497,1521]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,319,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-99@6.[151,1436,308,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Nazeris yujiei 23 forebody; 24 male sternite VII; 25 male sternite VIII; 26 aedeagus in ventral view; 27 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 23 1.0 mm; 24–27 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552225/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
) with triangular posterior excision. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[605,733,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1497,1521]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,319,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-99@6.[151,1436,308,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Nazeris yujiei 23 forebody; 24 male sternite VII; 25 male sternite VIII; 26 aedeagus in ventral view; 27 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 23 1.0 mm; 24–27 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552225/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Figs 26, 27</figureCitation>
) well sclerotized; ventral process short, narrowed apicad, with acute apex in ventral view; dorso-lateral apophyses moderately strong, with wide and round apex in ventral view, slightly curved in lateral view, extending beyond apex of ventral process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,556,510,537]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Distribution and habitat data.</emphasis>
The species is known from Xiaodanjiang, very close to Leigong Mt. in eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[151,251,547,573]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
. The specimens were collected by sifting leaf litter at an altitude of 
<specimenCount box="[1009,1087,547,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="generic">
<quantity box="[1009,1083,547,573]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" unit="m" value="700.0">700 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,434,582,609]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
The new species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lin, Yu &amp; Hu" authorityYear="2022" box="[842,1017,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nazeris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leigongensis">
<emphasis box="[842,1017,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">N. leigongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general appearance and separated only by the aedeagal characters: the acute apex of ventral process in ventral view, and the narrower dorso-lateral apophyses in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[450,535,655,682]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1497,1521]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,319,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-99@6.[151,1436,308,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Nazeris yujiei 23 forebody; 24 male sternite VII; 25 male sternite VIII; 26 aedeagus in ventral view; 27 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 23 1.0 mm; 24–27 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552225/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1232,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" box="[199,1232,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named in honor of Yu-Jie Cai, who collected the 
<typeStatus box="[1053,1101,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">type</typeStatus>
specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
